# Resolution is set by the HIGHEST patched bit output ("the LSB is the highest
# output you actually patch"), and patching may be non-contiguous.
# Two adc instances read the SAME input register I1 over the default range:
#   block A: 2 bits -> bit1=O1, bit2=O2            (N=2, 4 levels)
#   block B: bit1=O3, bit3=O4  (bit2 left unpatched) -> N=3, 8 levels
# Block B proves resolution follows the highest patched index (3), not the
# count of patched jacks (2): bit3 only carries a meaningful value if the range
# was divided into 8 pieces. Its unpatched bit2 is simply not emitted.
# SPEC-GAP: the manual assumes contiguous bit1..bitN patching; taking N as the
# maximum connected index is the literal reading of "highest output you patch".
#
#   input     A floor(in*4)  b1 b2 | B floor(in*8) value  b1(O3) b3(O4)
#   0.6875    2  = 10         1  0  | 5  = 101              1      1
#   0.3125    1  = 01         0  1  | 2  = 010              0      0
patch <<<
[adc]
    input = I1
    bit1 = O1
    bit2 = O2
>>>

patch <<<
[adc]
    input = I1
    bit1 = O3
    bit3 = O4
>>>

@0 set I1 0.6875
@0 expect O1 1
@0 expect O2 0
@0 expect O3 1
@0 expect O4 1

@1 set I1 0.3125
@1 expect O1 0
@1 expect O2 1
@1 expect O3 0
@1 expect O4 0
